Genes were first identified that contained mobile element insertions (MEIs) of either L1, Alu, or SVA.  These genes were then filtered to retain only genes with orthologs between human (hg19), chimp (panTro4), gorilla (GorGor3), orangutan (ponAbe2), and rhesus macaque (rheMac3). Locations of MEIs between humans and the respective non-human primate (NHP) were determined using mobile element annotation for each respective reference genome \citep{Kent2002}. Genes were classified as an MEI-containing gene if the MEI was within the gene transcription start to transcription stop sites, including introns. In order to compare between the sexes, only genes on the autosomes were considered in this analysis. Using data from Brawand et al., expression values were obtained for all of these genes and for each species. This dataset contained expression for multiple tissues, including brain, heart, kidney, liver, and testis.  The sample sizes of MEI-containing genes identified for each primate, and those with expression values from Brawand et al., were tabulated in table \ref{table:mei}.




The differences in expression across all species were controlled for by inter-sample normalization procedures (Brawand et al., 2011). Comparing between genes with MEIs versus genes without MEIs further controlled for differences in expression present across all genes. To determine if the presence of an MEI was associated with a general shift in gene expression, the odds ratio (OR) of increased expression in humans for genes containing MEIs versus genes not containing MEIs were calculated using the contingency table presented in table \ref{table:contablemei}. These ORs were calculated between human and each NHP for each tissue, MEI sub-type, and males and females separately (table \ref{table:permOR}).


\begin{table}
\large
\centering
\pgfplotstabletypeset[
  every head row/.style={%
    before row={\toprule 
        & \multicolumn{2}{c}{MEI-Status}\\
        \cmidrule{2-3}},
    after row=\midrule},
  every last row/.style={after row=\bottomrule},
  columns/{Higher Expression}/.style={string type},
  column type=r,
    columns/MEI/.style={string type},
    columns/no-MEI/.style={string type},
    columns/{Total by MEI}/.style={string type},
]{
    {Higher Expression}       MEI no-MEI  {Total by MEI}
    Human                   a           c               a+c 
    NHP                b           d               b+d 
    {Total by Expression}  a+b          c+d             a+b+c+d 
}
\caption[Contingency table for expression differences between human and non-human primate]{\normalsize{\textbf{Contingency table for expression differences between human and non-human primate\\}a,b,c, and represent counts of genes. Odds ratio = ad / bc}}
\label{table:contablemei}
\end{table}

Female humans were missing expression values for testis and liver; these tissues were therefore excluded from analysis in females. To minimize type I error, p-values were calculated directly by permuting MEI-status and a strict Bonferroni cutoff was calculated based on the total number of tests across all MEI types (Number of OR tests = 96; Bonferroni cutoff p = 5.21e-04) (table \ref{table:permOR}). Many ORs associated with Alu remained significant after Bonferroni correction (Alu: 16 of 32 ORs) (figure \ref{fig:meiplots}), indicating a tendency for gene expression to shift between species associated with MEI status. L1 and SVA ORs also showed significant results (L1: 1 of 32 ORs; SVA: 10 of 32 ORs). 


    %Figure boxplot of MEI Odds Ratios
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{meiplots2.pdf}
       \caption[The effect of MEI status on gene expression between primates]{\textbf{The effect of MEI status on gene expression between primates\\}
       Odds ratios for each tissue (brain, heart, liver, kidney, testis) and each primate (human, chimp, gorilla, orangutan, rhesus macaque) were plotted by MEI-type (Alu, L1, or SVA). Dots in black represented tests that did not pass Bonferonni significance ($\alpha$ = 1.25e-03 ). Dots in red represent tests that did pass Bonferroni significance.
       }
        \label{fig:meiplots}
    \end{figure}

Although it is possible that L1 and SVA are less often associated with genes that are expressed lower in humans than Alu, it is also possible that the reduced number of significant tests is due to a lack of power to detect significance due to their small sample numbers (req. effect size, Alu Chimp: 0.08; req. effect size, L1 Chimp: 0.48; req. effect size, SVA Chimp: 0.23). Interestingly, 76\% of the significant ORs were < 1 (Alu: 11 of 16 sig. tests (69\%); L1: 1 of 1 sig. tests (100\%); SVA: 8 of 11 sig. tests (72\%)), indicating an association of decreased gene expression in humans with the presence of an MEI. 

